WEBVTT

01:49.776 --> 01:50.878
Boy: I'll give you a boost
if you want.

01:50.902 --> 01:52.108
Laura: I don't need your help.

01:52.362 --> 01:54.068
Keith: Ooh. Hell,
she got you, buddy.

01:54.698 --> 01:56.484
Toss them beers. Here you go.

01:56.908 --> 01:58.819
You got it? Okay, let's go!

01:59.119 --> 02:01.405
All right. All right.

02:02.164 --> 02:03.244
Hold up, hold up! The beer.

02:03.624 --> 02:04.864
Take this. Take this. Come on.

02:06.960 --> 02:07.960
These damn shoes!

02:24.811 --> 02:27.644
Whoo! Come on in, it's warm!
Come on, buddy!

02:29.691 --> 02:32.103
Look, you can even wash your hair!

02:32.861 --> 02:34.351
I washed mine last month.

02:35.697 --> 02:37.153
Whoo!

02:43.830 --> 02:45.821
Laura, Keith, come here!
Look what I found.

02:46.708 --> 02:47.977
Scruffy boy: Holy shit.
Keith: What the hell's that?

02:48.001 --> 02:49.881
Laura: What is it?
Worker 1: The hell you doing?

02:50.128 --> 02:51.868
Get out of here, now!

02:52.255 --> 02:54.120
Geez! Come on!

02:58.178 --> 02:59.714
Worker: Goddamn kids.

03:17.155 --> 03:18.611
Turn off the beam, fool!

04:27.726 --> 04:30.342
Tom: Steve from dow,
Ted from union carbide...

04:30.812 --> 04:33.679
Jerry from exxon
and Andy from allied.

04:34.691 --> 04:36.522
Welcome to taft law, gentlemen.

04:37.736 --> 04:40.273
Before we get started,
a little housekeeping.

04:40.363 --> 04:42.228
Um, all of you know
this young man

04:42.324 --> 04:44.485
as the dedicated taft associate

04:44.576 --> 04:46.316
who for the past eight years has

04:47.287 --> 04:49.369
buried himself
in the superfund law.

04:49.664 --> 04:50.944
I'm not paying for that cleanup.

04:51.208 --> 04:53.699
Still it is my pleasure
to share with you

04:54.169 --> 04:57.332
that just last week, Rob bilott
was welcomed as a partner

04:57.422 --> 05:00.255
here at taft,
stettinius & Hollister.

05:03.470 --> 05:05.882
Good morning. Taft law.
One moment. I'll connect you.

05:09.267 --> 05:10.552
Good morning. Taft law.

05:11.561 --> 05:12.561
One moment, please.

05:16.608 --> 05:19.020
It's the governor's office
calling for uh,

05:19.694 --> 05:20.854
calling for Mr. Burke.

05:24.032 --> 05:25.032
May I help you?

05:25.408 --> 05:27.364
Wilbur tennant
calling on Robbie bilott.

05:28.078 --> 05:29.998
Rondell: Epa has saddled them
with the whole bill

05:30.038 --> 05:32.029
and given your client's
history at that site,

05:34.292 --> 05:38.160
I'll take it back to them.
Good. Tab 12, middletown...

05:38.338 --> 05:40.454
I know. I'm sorry.

05:40.966 --> 05:43.127
But they won't leave.
Who's they?

05:43.927 --> 05:46.168
I don't know.
They say they know you.

05:50.851 --> 05:53.308
Um... Robert bilott?

05:53.770 --> 05:56.227
Um, yes.

05:57.899 --> 06:00.641
They call it a landfill.
A dump's what it is.

06:01.319 --> 06:03.856
They told my brother and me
no chemicals, just trash.

06:03.947 --> 06:05.187
But we ain't stupid.

06:05.448 --> 06:08.030
I made them videotapes myself.
All the proof you need.

06:08.118 --> 06:09.998
They're poisonin' the creek,
killing my animals.

06:10.078 --> 06:12.118
I'm in the middle of a meeting.
So, I want a lawyer.

06:12.205 --> 06:14.821
Every damn one in parkersburg's
too yella to take my case.

06:14.916 --> 06:16.622
Rob. He wants you back in there.

06:16.710 --> 06:18.541
They all scared shitless
at dupont.

06:18.628 --> 06:19.868
Well, I ain't scared of nobody.

06:19.963 --> 06:21.544
Okay. Kathleen is my paralegal.

06:21.631 --> 06:23.747
She's gonna give you
a directory of lawyers.

06:23.842 --> 06:25.252
That's why
I called your grandma.

06:27.596 --> 06:29.552
What? My neighbor who tells me,

06:29.639 --> 06:30.799
call Alma white.

06:31.474 --> 06:34.466
Her grandson's some fancy environment
lawyer down in Cincinnati.

06:39.858 --> 06:43.100
Sir, I am a corporate
defense attorney.

06:43.570 --> 06:46.027
S07?
I defend chemical companies.

06:46.156 --> 06:48.989
Well, now you can defend me.
Tom: Rob!

06:50.368 --> 06:52.233
Uh, 30 seconds, Tom.

06:53.204 --> 06:55.115
Uh, I'm sorry, Mr... Tennant.

06:55.582 --> 06:57.243
I can offer you a referral.

06:57.334 --> 07:00.201
But I just don't see how I
can be of any help to you.

07:00.295 --> 07:02.377
You can start by watching
them tapes for one thing.

07:02.464 --> 07:03.954
Oh, let's go, Earl.

07:04.090 --> 07:06.877
I'm sorry.
I... I wish you all the luck.

07:06.968 --> 07:08.237
I don't need
your damn luck, boy!

07:08.261 --> 07:09.626
I need your help! Tom: Rob!

07:13.058 --> 07:14.138
Come on.

07:21.358 --> 07:23.394
I'm not arguing
with the overall analysis.

07:23.818 --> 07:26.560
My only point is that
whatever we decide upon...

07:32.243 --> 07:33.403
Lawyer: Thank you, gentlemen.

07:35.872 --> 07:37.072
Do you know where we're going?

07:37.916 --> 07:39.656
There's a place
right around the corner.

07:39.793 --> 07:41.829
Yeah? What the hell
was that all about?

07:42.963 --> 07:45.420
He knows my grandmother. Really?

07:45.715 --> 07:47.876
Well, my mom's from
West Virginia.

07:47.968 --> 07:49.833
Uh, from a town, parkersburg.

07:50.303 --> 07:52.760
Not us. My...
My father was air force.

07:52.847 --> 07:54.053
We... we moved around a lot,

07:54.140 --> 07:55.368
but we spent the summers there.

07:55.392 --> 07:57.633
Dow lawyer: Come on, terp. You're buying.
Of course I am.

07:59.396 --> 08:01.227
You can be
from West Virginia, Rob.

08:02.148 --> 08:03.513
I won't tell anyone.

08:09.322 --> 08:11.404
Tom: All right, gentlemen.
Morton's it is.

08:13.284 --> 08:15.525
Still deigned to eat
with us lowly associates?

08:18.164 --> 08:19.745
You can't drive an American car.

08:21.167 --> 08:24.000
Taft-hartley, union busting?

08:24.087 --> 08:25.748
We practically invented it.

08:26.006 --> 08:27.041
"We?"

08:27.132 --> 08:28.963
Besides, I know
a highly esteemed partner

08:29.050 --> 08:30.130
who still drives American.

08:30.218 --> 08:31.503
Some real clunkers too. Okay,

08:31.678 --> 08:33.339
yeah, but he collects them.

08:33.513 --> 08:35.128
That's different. Like his

08:35.223 --> 08:36.713
no-name college and law school.

08:36.808 --> 08:38.035
No offense. Are you
listening to this?

08:38.059 --> 08:39.390
Hey, you guys go ahead,
all right?

08:39.894 --> 08:42.385
Look, I didn't mean anything by it.
No. I gotta make a call.

08:42.480 --> 08:43.541
It's all right.
I'll see you there.

08:43.565 --> 08:44.930
Okay, we'll save you a fish log.

08:47.777 --> 08:50.018
You can be such an asshole.
James: Karla, it was a joke.

08:50.572 --> 08:51.932
Karla: Yeah.
James: We always joke.

08:51.990 --> 08:54.030
Karla: Oh, yeah. You guys are
a couple of jokesters.

09:03.376 --> 09:06.288
Alma: You've
reached the residence of Alma white.

09:06.755 --> 09:08.620
I can't come to the phone
right now...

09:09.716 --> 09:12.048
He's good. He's home
early tonight actually.

09:13.219 --> 09:15.050
Sarah's mom: Tell him I
said, howdy, partner.

09:15.555 --> 09:16.635
She says, "howdy, partner."

09:17.098 --> 09:18.804
Are we ever gonna
see him again on Sundays?

09:18.892 --> 09:20.928
Yes, he can still come
to Sunday dinners, mom.

09:21.019 --> 09:23.179
He's a partner, not the
President of the United States.

09:23.229 --> 09:25.015
I wanna make...
Do you have my bundt pan?

09:25.106 --> 09:26.106
Returned it.

09:26.191 --> 09:27.293
Where?
I looked under the counter.

09:27.317 --> 09:29.683
It's the right hand cupboard,
in the plastic. Yeah.

09:30.945 --> 09:32.560
Okay, well, we just sat down.

09:32.655 --> 09:33.655
All right, dear.

09:33.740 --> 09:34.820
So, I gotta go.

09:34.908 --> 09:35.908
Love to Rob and Teddy.

09:35.992 --> 09:37.512
All right, see you Sunday.
Love to dad.

09:37.577 --> 09:38.577
Talk to you later.

09:38.661 --> 09:39.972
Can you pretend to be
surprised about the cake?

09:39.996 --> 09:41.327
She wants it to be very special.

09:42.248 --> 09:44.239
Oh, and the granite samples
came in.

09:44.334 --> 09:45.853
Can you pick them up
on your way home tomorrow?

09:45.877 --> 09:47.333
Mmm. Rob?

09:47.587 --> 09:48.702
Hmm? Uh, sure.

09:55.595 --> 09:56.630
You okay?

09:57.097 --> 09:58.097
Yes.

09:59.015 --> 10:00.380
Bless us, our lord and thy gifts

10:00.475 --> 10:02.161
which we are about to receive
from thy bounty

10:02.185 --> 10:03.391
through Christ our lord. Amen.

10:03.728 --> 10:05.559
Thank you, god.
Thank you for our family.

11:04.831 --> 11:05.831
Thank you.

11:45.788 --> 11:50.202
Hi, grammers. What on earth!

11:52.337 --> 11:54.023
I tried to call,
but you weren't picking up.

11:54.047 --> 11:57.414
Alma: Oh, well, you know me.
My two fake knees.

11:57.508 --> 12:00.750
What are you doing here?

12:02.680 --> 12:05.763
A farmer came to see me.

12:08.186 --> 12:09.471
Wilbur tennant?

12:09.979 --> 12:11.185
You do know him.

12:11.272 --> 12:14.355
I don't socialize with him,
if that's what you mean.

12:16.027 --> 12:18.734
Inez Graham owned the farm
next to his.

12:19.322 --> 12:22.064
I used to take you and Beth over
there when you were little.

12:23.201 --> 12:24.281
That's the place?

12:38.299 --> 12:39.299
Hmm.

12:41.135 --> 12:42.841
You rode that pony. Ar!

12:44.514 --> 12:45.924
Rob: I loved that place.

12:47.141 --> 12:49.132
Alma: Saw a cow
for the first time.

12:50.019 --> 12:51.099
Learned to milk it.

12:51.980 --> 12:53.720
I remember
you sittin' there for hours

12:53.815 --> 12:56.272
making sure you got
every last drop.

12:56.818 --> 12:57.933
Just like you.

12:59.779 --> 13:00.779
There.

13:01.698 --> 13:02.698
Rob: Hmm.

13:03.199 --> 13:04.484
So you gonna help him?

13:05.493 --> 13:06.493
Huh?

13:55.168 --> 13:58.626
You come up the holler,
dump's up the hill.

14:01.924 --> 14:04.085
Since I started
complaining about my creek,

14:04.177 --> 14:06.543
fence goes up. All blocked off.

14:12.560 --> 14:13.845
Hi, I'm Rob.

14:14.604 --> 14:15.604
Sandra.

14:17.148 --> 14:21.187
Wilbur: The state, any veterinarian
I've called in parkersburg,

14:22.445 --> 14:24.527
they will not
return my phone calls.

14:24.614 --> 14:26.195
Like I bite the hand that feeds.

14:26.282 --> 14:28.442
No, it's all right. I've already...
This here's a gall.

14:28.910 --> 14:30.262
Look at the size of it.
Ain't never seen

14:30.286 --> 14:31.992
no gall that big.
Bigger than the heart.

14:33.206 --> 14:34.412
That your cows'?

14:34.499 --> 14:35.579
Look at them teeth.

14:38.294 --> 14:40.501
Black as night. Here.

14:44.258 --> 14:46.715
Hoof, all turned in on itself.

14:46.803 --> 14:48.794
Half my calves born
with hooves like that.

14:52.392 --> 14:54.599
Tumor, I done
cut off the back a heifer.

14:54.685 --> 14:56.266
How'd ya like
that on your table?

15:00.566 --> 15:02.181
Rob: What am I looking for?

15:03.277 --> 15:04.517
You blind, boy?

15:05.321 --> 15:07.903
Stones as white
as the hairs on my head.

15:09.075 --> 15:11.532
Bleached! That's chemicals,
I'm telling ya.

15:13.162 --> 15:16.245
My animals drink this water.
Cool off in 'er.

15:16.833 --> 15:19.666
Get them bloody welts,
them dead eyes.

15:19.752 --> 15:21.743
Charge at me, crazy-like.

15:21.838 --> 15:23.874
Animals that used to eat
out of my own hand.

15:29.387 --> 15:30.667
Rob: Where are the rest of them?

15:32.515 --> 15:33.595
Come on.

15:46.279 --> 15:49.442
Beginnin', I'd bury 'em.
Each one. They're family.

15:51.159 --> 15:54.196
It got to be so many,
pile 'em up, set fire to...

15:57.665 --> 15:59.872
How many did you lose?

16:00.501 --> 16:02.958
190.

16:04.547 --> 16:06.663
190 cows?

16:06.757 --> 16:08.668
You tell me
nothing's wrong here.

16:16.142 --> 16:19.885
And this landfill
wasn't always here?

16:20.605 --> 16:24.974
No. My brother Jim used to dig
ditches over at the dupont plant.

16:25.234 --> 16:27.600
Got sick, couldn't
do it no more.

16:27.904 --> 16:30.896
One day they come to him, offering to
buy his land right up that holler.

16:32.200 --> 16:34.191
They promised no chemicals.

16:34.410 --> 16:37.026
And I assume you
reached out to dupont?

16:37.121 --> 16:38.986
Dupont, the state, the feds.

16:39.081 --> 16:41.447
I called everybody
there is dozens of times.

16:42.168 --> 16:44.580
Epa finally comes out here.
Oh, they did.

16:44.837 --> 16:47.579
All for some report.
What did it say?

16:47.924 --> 16:49.380
You think they're gonna show me?

17:15.284 --> 17:16.444
Sarah: Okay.

17:20.623 --> 17:24.866
He's been like this all day.
Okay. Go on.

17:29.924 --> 17:32.006
Of course, you're
a perfect angel for daddy.

17:34.720 --> 17:38.133
Did you get the tile?
Um, I'm sorry. No.

17:39.392 --> 17:40.472
Rob.

17:42.687 --> 17:44.348
I didn't drive into town today.
I'm sorry.

17:45.314 --> 17:47.475
What do you mean
you didn't drive into town?

17:48.109 --> 17:49.565
I had to go to parkersburg.

17:50.903 --> 17:53.269
Parkersburg? Why'd you
have to go to parkersburg?

17:54.657 --> 17:56.648
I may have a client there.

17:57.493 --> 18:00.530
In West Virginia? What kind
of a case would you have?

18:01.581 --> 18:04.448
He's a farmer. He knows
my grammer. Not well, but...

18:05.167 --> 18:09.080
So, you saw her?
Was your mother there?

18:09.171 --> 18:12.413
Oh, come on, Sarah. I didn't
sneak off to see my mother.

18:13.342 --> 18:15.674
So, why did you sneak off?
I didn't.

18:18.681 --> 18:21.969
Our speaker tonight's no
stranger to the taft family.

18:22.977 --> 18:25.764
Phillip Donnelly, Phil to us,

18:26.188 --> 18:28.895
serves as in-house
corporate counsel at dupont.

18:29.692 --> 18:33.355
Not only one of America's most
revered chemical companies,

18:34.030 --> 18:36.942
but one of the few
giants of the industry

18:37.033 --> 18:40.241
that taft doesn't represent.
Not yet anyway!

18:40.745 --> 18:42.906
Managing partner:
That's the spirit, James.

18:44.123 --> 18:47.661
We asked Phil here tonight, not
just to show him what he's missing,

18:48.044 --> 18:51.286
but to hear how a renowned
leader of our industry

18:51.839 --> 18:55.798
stays that way.
Please welcome Phil Donnelly.

18:59.305 --> 19:01.387
Wish me luck. Go get 'em, Phil!

19:02.558 --> 19:06.050
At dupont, we're not producing
chemicals for chemical's sake.

19:06.145 --> 19:07.885
We're producing them
for people's sake.

19:08.147 --> 19:10.513
To make folks' lives easier.

19:10.983 --> 19:13.065
Happier, longer.

19:14.403 --> 19:18.612
That's why better living
through chemistry

19:19.450 --> 19:21.486
is not just a slogan at dupont.

19:23.079 --> 19:24.660
It's our DNA.

19:29.752 --> 19:31.583
Hey, Rob. Hello, Phil.

19:31.712 --> 19:34.078
Is it true what Tom tells me?
Yeah, it's true.

19:34.173 --> 19:36.533
Well, good on them. They're lucky
to have you. Thanks, Phil.

19:36.717 --> 19:38.457
Like I always tell
my younger associates,

19:38.552 --> 19:40.793
just keep your head down
and do the work.

19:40.888 --> 19:45.052
Thanks. Uh, Phil, can I ask
you sort of an odd question?

19:45.267 --> 19:46.473
Shoot.

19:46.644 --> 19:49.135
Does the name
wilbur tennant ring a bell?

19:50.398 --> 19:52.229
Tennet, did you say? Tennant.

19:52.775 --> 19:54.060
No. Not that I recall.

19:54.151 --> 19:56.767
Mr. tennant"s a farmer
from West Virginia.

19:56.862 --> 20:00.070
His property abuts one of
your landfills, dry run.

20:00.157 --> 20:01.818
And his cows
have been getting sick.

20:01.909 --> 20:05.993
He thinks possibly because of the runoff
from the landfill into his creek.

20:06.080 --> 20:07.820
You're kidding me.
How did this come to you?

20:07.915 --> 20:11.078
Kim: Hey, Phil!
He's a farmer. He's...

20:12.044 --> 20:14.080
My grandmother's
from parkersburg.

20:14.171 --> 20:16.253
Really? Washington works.
Great plant.

20:16.382 --> 20:18.873
Right. She knows the tennants.
So grandma's on your back?

20:18.968 --> 20:20.708
Something like that.
Anyway, uh...

20:21.971 --> 20:25.555
The farmer said the epa came out,
took a look around. I wondered...

20:25.725 --> 20:27.590
The name of the landfill again?
Dry run.

20:28.060 --> 20:29.721
Dry run. Dry...

20:30.062 --> 20:32.082
You know, that does ring a
bell, now that you mention it.

20:32.106 --> 20:33.937
We may have even sent
some folks out there.

20:34.191 --> 20:36.147
If I remember correctly,
help epa check it out.

20:36.235 --> 20:39.477
That's gotta be it. So, I'd love
to share whatever came of that

20:39.572 --> 20:41.608
with Mr. tennant.
Help settle his nerves.

20:41.741 --> 20:44.528
Absolutely. Soon as I'm back in
Wilmington, I'll take a look.

20:44.660 --> 20:47.493
Thanks, Phil. I really appreciate it.
Happy to do it.

20:47.580 --> 20:50.947
Now, let's get a drink and
toast you, my friend. You.

20:51.917 --> 20:53.032
Okay.

21:01.218 --> 21:02.458
Mr. tennant!

21:10.144 --> 21:13.011
Mr. tennant, I have the report.

21:15.357 --> 21:18.394
Sons of bitches! Who the
hell they think they are?

21:19.195 --> 21:21.186
Who gives them the right?
It's an evaluation.

21:21.280 --> 21:24.067
Evalu, hatchet job's what it is.

21:25.075 --> 21:28.238
I been farming my
entire life. Entire lifel

21:28.662 --> 21:31.529
you read that. You tell me
you recognize my farm.

21:31.624 --> 21:33.080
Mr. tennant... read it!

21:36.462 --> 21:38.999
"The herd health
investigation revealed

21:39.089 --> 21:41.375
"deficiency in herd management.

21:42.092 --> 21:44.674
"Including poor nutrition,

21:45.304 --> 21:49.889
"inadequate veterinary care
and lack of fly control."

21:50.100 --> 21:51.681
You see any flies here?

21:52.812 --> 21:53.892
It's snowing.

21:54.188 --> 21:56.349
Can't stop making excuses
for 'em, can you?

21:58.108 --> 22:00.941
It could be pests.
They consulted a vet.

22:01.195 --> 22:02.776
Whose vet? Dupont?

22:06.116 --> 22:09.825
Look at yourself. Swallowin' whole,
whatever they been feeding ya.

22:09.912 --> 22:11.152
Can't tell truth from lie.

22:13.624 --> 22:15.080
You even watch them tapes
I gave you?

22:15.167 --> 22:18.375
Sir, I am trying to help! Quiet.

22:19.046 --> 22:21.458
Trying to help. Stop movin'.

22:29.348 --> 22:31.509
Easy, now. Easy.

22:35.104 --> 22:37.470
Get in. Slow.

23:03.924 --> 23:05.209
Forgive me, girl.

23:29.575 --> 23:31.031
Jesus.

24:25.923 --> 24:28.123
Radio dj: Need something to
warm you up right about now?

24:28.550 --> 24:30.541
Well, how about this?

24:34.348 --> 24:39.058
Man:
Almost heaven, West Virginia

24:40.104 --> 24:45.940
blue Ridge mountains,
shenandoah river

24:47.361 --> 24:52.321
life is old there,
older than the trees

24:52.449 --> 24:57.489
younger than the mountains
blowing like the breeze

24:57.663 --> 25:03.033
country roads, take me home

25:03.419 --> 25:06.126
to the place...

25:06.463 --> 25:09.170
I belong

25:09.341 --> 25:12.003
West Virginia...

25:12.219 --> 25:14.881
Mountain mama

25:15.180 --> 25:17.296
take me home...

25:17.516 --> 25:22.476
Wilbur: This cow's eyes are cloudy
with pink eyes is what they'll call it.

25:22.771 --> 25:25.137
Anyway, her eyes are sunk
way back in her head.

25:25.899 --> 25:29.016
She's poor as a whippoorwill.

25:30.779 --> 25:35.443
And I'm gonna cut her open and
find out what caused her to die.

25:36.160 --> 25:37.946
Because I was feeding
her enough feed...

25:38.037 --> 25:40.403
That she should've gained weight
instead of losin' weight.

25:41.457 --> 25:43.072
This is what
her teeth looks like.

25:45.669 --> 25:47.660
That's the upper one.

25:47.838 --> 25:52.423
But this one here, I've never seen
anything like it in my lifetime.

25:53.802 --> 25:55.242
Even the veterinarian,
he admitted...

25:55.304 --> 25:58.888
He never saw anything like this
before in his life either.

26:08.776 --> 26:13.315
So, what are you
proposing we do?

26:13.489 --> 26:17.983
File a claim, trigger discovery and
find out what's in that landfill.

26:18.952 --> 26:20.988
You wanna sue dupont? Targeted.

26:22.122 --> 26:25.706
Property dispute. Routine stuff.
Not routine. Not around here.

26:25.793 --> 26:28.375
I know, but, Tom,
if you'd actually seen it.

26:28.462 --> 26:32.546
His farm is like a graveyard.
There's something very wrong.

26:32.633 --> 26:35.215
So, he should
hire a local lawyer.

26:35.302 --> 26:38.135
None of them will do it. They're
all terrified of dupont.

26:38.263 --> 26:40.424
Well, what does that tell you?
We know dupont.

26:41.183 --> 26:42.719
They're gonna wanna hear

26:42.810 --> 26:45.472
if some of their local guys
are screwing something up.

26:45.562 --> 26:48.554
Oh, so they're gonna
thank us for suing.

26:48.649 --> 26:50.185
Better us than the epa.

26:50.442 --> 26:52.933
I mean, new partners are supposed
to bring in business, right?

26:53.028 --> 26:55.440
So, your farmer
can swing 275 an hour?

26:55.531 --> 26:57.442
It'd be on contingency.

26:58.033 --> 27:01.070
Jesus. What are we,
coupon chasers now?

27:01.161 --> 27:04.904
It's a small matter for a family friend.
I'll get in and I'll get out.

27:06.125 --> 27:09.663
Help a guy that needs it.
Who? The farmer or you?

27:30.107 --> 27:32.018
Surgical. You hear me?

27:32.109 --> 27:33.440
Absolutely. Thank you.

27:35.946 --> 27:38.779
Phil: Come on, Rob. Of
course, I'm gonna take your call.

27:39.032 --> 27:41.774
Even though, I was,
I admit, a little surprised.

27:42.077 --> 27:44.284
I mean, getting
sued by taft law.

27:45.122 --> 27:47.829
It's not every day.
Or any day, frankly.

27:48.000 --> 27:49.331
I know. I'm sorry.

27:49.418 --> 27:52.910
Look, you and I are friends.
This is a minor issue.

27:53.005 --> 27:55.212
No reason it should get messy.

27:55.299 --> 27:59.133
Thank you. I totally agree. Yeah,
I'm putting you on speaker phone.

28:01.180 --> 28:04.422
So, you wanna know
if we violated our permits.

28:04.725 --> 28:05.760
Pretty much, yeah.

28:06.393 --> 28:09.009
Okay, then. I'll have our
guys send over anything...

28:09.104 --> 28:11.436
Related to hazardous wastes
at dry run.

28:11.523 --> 28:14.686
And I'll tell them to hurry
it up this time. How's that?

28:14.776 --> 28:18.314
Thank you. That sounds great. And
don't stress. I forgive you.

28:18.697 --> 28:19.732
Thanks, Phil.

28:41.845 --> 28:43.301
You took your baby
into the office?

28:43.388 --> 28:46.471
I needed a bigger trunk. Why?

28:47.100 --> 28:49.591
Discovery for the tennant
case came in today.

28:49.686 --> 28:54.680
Oh. Oh, you started before me.
You're so fast! Whoa.

28:54.775 --> 28:56.561
Good boy.

28:56.652 --> 28:58.563
Rob's missing such a lovely day.

28:59.529 --> 29:02.692
Law's a jealous mistress, mom.
Means it comes with the territory.

29:02.783 --> 29:04.114
Let's go over here!

29:04.451 --> 29:07.451
Sarah's brother: Nice! Thank you! That's
what I'm talking about right there.

29:11.291 --> 29:13.291
All right. Let's go. One more.
One more. All right.

29:32.187 --> 29:33.302
Poly...

29:33.480 --> 29:34.640
Is that...

29:51.456 --> 29:52.946
No.

30:00.340 --> 30:03.173
How's my favorite plaintiff's attorney?
Hey, help me out, will ya?

30:03.260 --> 30:05.626
You're a run of a mill
dump, nothing but trash.

30:05.804 --> 30:07.294
You sound like
my first girlfriend.

30:08.807 --> 30:13.016
Why a requisition order
for 55-gallon containers?

30:13.395 --> 30:15.681
Conspiracy. Standard size drums.

30:15.772 --> 30:20.812
Ash, ash-byproduct, glass tubing,
plastic, paper waste. It's just trash.

30:20.986 --> 30:23.853
You pile it onto a truck, drive it away.
You don't pack it into drums.

30:23.989 --> 30:26.355
So, they've got liquid waste.
Not hazardous.

30:26.825 --> 30:30.158
Or they'd have to disclose it.
So, what is killing these cows?

30:30.329 --> 30:32.741
It's not paper and ash. Well,
maybe it's human error.

30:32.914 --> 30:35.274
They're dumping something in
there they don't know is toxic.

30:35.625 --> 30:39.584
Kim, it's dupont. They know
more than the epa does.

30:39.755 --> 30:41.666
Everyone knows more
than the epa does.

30:41.840 --> 30:43.796
Why else would they
let us regulate ourselves?

30:46.136 --> 30:48.878
What? Do we?

30:49.097 --> 30:50.507
Do we what?

30:51.808 --> 30:54.891
The epa only started
regulating chemicals in '76.

30:54.978 --> 30:56.013
Yeah?

30:56.104 --> 30:59.688
They grandfather in every
existing chemical, non-hazardous,

30:59.775 --> 31:03.734
unless they knew it was hazardous
or a company told them it was.

31:03.820 --> 31:06.527
We're saying the same thing.
No, we're not. I'm saying

31:06.615 --> 31:10.107
what if a company didn't tell?

31:11.828 --> 31:13.534
What if

31:13.622 --> 31:17.410
the reason Phil Donnelly agreed
to discovery on hazardous

31:17.501 --> 31:19.116
is because he knows

31:19.753 --> 31:22.836
whatever's in that landfill
isn't even regulated?

31:23.215 --> 31:25.957
Okay, now you are sounding
like a plaintiff's attorney.

31:26.551 --> 31:29.167
I've got a meeting.
Hey, oh, wait, one second.

31:29.388 --> 31:33.176
Have you heard of this,
um, pfoa?

31:34.101 --> 31:35.216
No.

31:35.435 --> 31:38.723
You know, it's mentioned here, but
I can't find anything about it

31:38.814 --> 31:41.294
in any of the literature. I don't
even know if it's a chemical.

31:41.858 --> 31:44.850
Ask Phil. Well, thank you.

31:45.529 --> 31:48.249
Secretary: As I said, Mr.
Donnelly is still out of town.

31:48.323 --> 31:51.907
I called last week and left two messages
and haven't heard back from him.

31:51.993 --> 31:53.833
I'll be sure to tell him
that you called again.

31:53.912 --> 31:55.573
Okay. Damn it.

31:56.873 --> 31:59.330
Your tickets to the chemical
alliance dinner. Argh...

31:59.668 --> 32:02.455
And, no, dark suit is not
the same as black tie.

32:04.047 --> 32:05.127
Wouldn't he be going?

32:35.871 --> 32:39.034
I don't know if Rob told you, but
I was a receptionist at taft

32:39.124 --> 32:40.614
before law school.
Is that right?

32:40.709 --> 32:42.669
But well, I think the
right bilott ended up there.

32:42.752 --> 32:44.413
Harold, you're not
getting away from me.

32:44.504 --> 32:46.369
Would you excuse me?
Sure, it was...

32:46.465 --> 32:48.831
It's great to see you.
When is the...

32:48.925 --> 32:50.881
That's funny.

32:51.636 --> 32:54.343
Right away, I saw a little
of myself in Rob.

32:54.514 --> 32:56.630
Oh! One black sheep to another.

32:56.808 --> 32:59.094
My dad was a steel worker, you know.
Was he?

32:59.269 --> 33:01.180
Have you seen Phil?

33:01.730 --> 33:03.220
Kim: No.

33:03.523 --> 33:06.890
So, you're an attorney?
Oh, recovering.

33:07.194 --> 33:09.685
I represented employers
in workmen's comp disputes.

33:09.779 --> 33:12.020
But now, I stay at home
with our baby.

33:12.365 --> 33:14.902
Well, that's the thing
with lady lawyers.

33:15.660 --> 33:17.221
I wanna say hi to the dow folks.
Have you seen them?

33:17.245 --> 33:18.655
No, I've been looking for Phil.

33:18.747 --> 33:20.227
Did I tell you they
sent me some work?

33:20.332 --> 33:23.790
Dow? That's great! Just a small project.
Like a try-out.

33:23.877 --> 33:27.165
But if I impress them, can you
imagine if I brought on dow?

33:27.255 --> 33:29.792
None for me, thank you.

33:30.884 --> 33:31.919
You're not...

33:34.095 --> 33:35.095
I'm, uh...

33:36.348 --> 33:38.259
You're... she's...

33:38.350 --> 33:40.011
I'm...

33:40.101 --> 33:42.968
I'm gonna wait as long as I can
to tell the firm. Obviously.

33:43.063 --> 33:44.644
Would you excuse
us for a moment?

33:44.731 --> 33:46.813
These lady lawyers
need a quick sidebar.

33:46.900 --> 33:48.265
Of course. No. No.

33:48.360 --> 33:50.520
He signs your paycheck. Be nice to him.
Don't leave me.

33:52.989 --> 33:55.401
Sarah: Congratulations. Karla: I know.
I can't believe it.

34:01.331 --> 34:02.411
Excuse me.

34:12.133 --> 34:13.339
Phil: Rob, how are you?

34:13.426 --> 34:14.820
Phil, I've been
trying to reach you.

34:14.844 --> 34:16.739
So sorry, all this traveling. How
about I give you a shout tomorrow?

34:16.763 --> 34:18.616
We're gonna need to broaden
discovery to everything

34:18.640 --> 34:20.380
in that landfill,
hazardous or not.

34:24.563 --> 34:25.598
Excuse me.

34:26.690 --> 34:28.055
You kidding me?

34:28.149 --> 34:29.149
Rob: No.

34:31.653 --> 34:33.814
I think whatever's causing
the problems in there

34:33.905 --> 34:36.988
isn't something the epa
regulates or knows to regulate.

34:37.617 --> 34:38.617
Sorry?

34:38.702 --> 34:42.035
I'm seeing things in your
documents I don't understand.

34:42.122 --> 34:44.362
You're seeing ghosts, is what
you're seeing, and frankly,

34:44.416 --> 34:45.747
you're making an
ass of yourself.

34:45.834 --> 34:47.495
Okay, then, help me out.

34:47.586 --> 34:48.826
I mean, like this.

34:48.920 --> 34:52.162
I mean, what is this pfoa?

34:52.841 --> 34:54.502
What's that stand for?

34:56.344 --> 34:57.629
Jesus.

34:57.721 --> 35:00.007
You're on a goddamn
fishing expedition.

35:00.640 --> 35:03.097
You wanna flush your
career down the toilet

35:03.184 --> 35:04.219
for some cowhand?

35:04.311 --> 35:05.892
Be my guest. I'm
done helping you.

35:05.979 --> 35:08.436
Phil, I need to insist
on broadening discovery.

35:08.773 --> 35:09.808
Sue me! Uh...

35:10.900 --> 35:11.935
I'm already suing you.

35:12.027 --> 35:13.233
Dow lawyer: Welcome, everyone,

35:13.320 --> 35:16.778
to the 14th annual Ohio
chemical alliance...

35:16.865 --> 35:18.480
Fuck you! Awards dinner.

35:21.494 --> 35:22.529
Hick!

35:25.999 --> 35:28.991
Dow lawyer: So, let's
get the fun started!

35:49.939 --> 35:51.520
I'm sorry.

35:51.608 --> 35:53.564
Sarah: You're not the only
one who's sacrificed.

35:59.949 --> 36:02.136
I just hope
you know what you're doing.

36:08.750 --> 36:10.978
Tom: You know the difference between
business and pleasure, right?

36:11.002 --> 36:14.620
So, why on earth would you
engage in business conversations

36:14.714 --> 36:16.625
at a public function? Rob: Tom!

36:17.425 --> 36:19.962
He's hiding something.
You saw his reaction.

36:20.053 --> 36:21.839
Yeah, me and everyone
in that room.

36:21.930 --> 36:23.795
Taft in a pissing
match with dupont.

36:23.890 --> 36:25.801
I am gonna get a court
order and force them

36:25.892 --> 36:27.244
to tell me everything
that's in that landfill.

36:27.268 --> 36:29.600
Jesus Christ! Now you wanna
actually take them to court.

36:29.688 --> 36:31.724
And I'm gonna need local
counsel in West Virginia.

36:31.815 --> 36:33.396
What happened to routine stuff?

36:33.483 --> 36:35.348
Ask Phil Donnelly. God!

36:36.277 --> 36:37.557
Larry: Of course,
I remember you.

36:38.822 --> 36:41.108
Yeah, last time I saw you,
I think Phil Donnelly was

36:41.199 --> 36:43.485
trying to get you to go
out on the links with us.

36:43.576 --> 36:44.611
Yeah.

36:47.497 --> 36:48.532
You what?

37:02.429 --> 37:03.714
Sir. Thank you.

37:10.019 --> 37:11.019
Good morning.

37:14.566 --> 37:15.931
Good morning, Larry. Morning.

37:22.782 --> 37:23.782
Morning, miss Claire.

37:25.076 --> 37:26.737
Don't you look nice.

37:26.828 --> 37:28.238
Save it for the
judge, Mr. winter.

37:32.500 --> 37:34.991
Filing clerk:
You're suing dupont.

37:37.046 --> 37:38.081
Larry: Yes, ma'am.

37:38.715 --> 37:40.455
You represent dupont.

37:40.550 --> 37:41.550
My old firm did.

37:42.552 --> 37:43.952
I've been out on
my own for a while.

37:45.680 --> 37:46.920
Good luck with that.

37:51.478 --> 37:53.844
Phil: Just wanted to
let you know personally

37:53.938 --> 37:57.271
that your court-ordered
discovery is on the way.

37:57.358 --> 37:58.939
Thanks, Phil.

37:59.027 --> 38:01.109
Phil: No, it's my pleasure.

38:03.448 --> 38:04.528
Discovery.

38:20.423 --> 38:22.004
Son of a bitch.

38:22.091 --> 38:24.423
No admission of liability.

38:25.303 --> 38:26.964
And non...

38:29.390 --> 38:31.847
Non-disclosure of
any and all terms.

38:33.645 --> 38:34.760
Pardon me a moment.

38:50.036 --> 38:51.242
Thanks.

38:52.080 --> 38:53.945
Holy Jesus!

38:54.999 --> 38:56.330
What in the... thanks.

38:58.169 --> 38:59.375
World?

38:59.462 --> 39:01.544
I guess the joke's on me.

39:01.631 --> 39:02.631
Yeah.

39:04.092 --> 39:05.945
No one can go through all this crap.
Not in a million years.

39:05.969 --> 39:08.049
Yeah, I'm pretty sure that's
what they're banking on.

39:10.640 --> 39:12.756
Oh, god! Damn it! Oh, god, Rob!

39:18.147 --> 39:21.230
Here, let me... no, no, no, you
shouldn't be around this stuff.

39:22.569 --> 39:25.481
You sure? I'm positive.
Thank you, though.

39:26.239 --> 39:27.274
Yeah.

39:28.783 --> 39:29.818
Good luck.

39:51.347 --> 39:52.803
1957.

