They been here!

49:17.455 --> 49:18.570
What happened?

49:20.416 --> 49:21.416
Wash up.

49:30.718 --> 49:31.753
Crystal: Dad?

49:34.513 --> 49:35.548
What is it? Quiet.

49:45.858 --> 49:49.146
Wilbur: This is my land,
damn you! You get out of here!

49:49.904 --> 49:50.939
Go on!

49:52.406 --> 49:53.521
Go on!

49:55.242 --> 49:59.076
Sandra, girls, get on!
Go on, get in! Get in!

50:01.165 --> 50:02.496
I know you!

52:14.840 --> 52:15.875
Rob?

52:41.659 --> 52:45.072
Holy crap, Rob! What?

52:45.162 --> 52:47.949
I thought someone was
breaking in, for god's sakes!

52:48.040 --> 52:49.496
No, it's just me.

52:49.583 --> 52:51.663
Rob, you need to tell me
what in the hell's going on.

52:54.797 --> 52:56.128
We're being poisoned.

52:59.009 --> 53:00.419
Rob. What?

53:00.511 --> 53:04.174
I mean it. Dupont is
knowingly poisoning us.

53:04.264 --> 53:06.550
You mean the farmer. His land.

53:07.393 --> 53:08.473
All of us.

53:10.729 --> 53:12.139
Please don't look at me
like that.

53:13.691 --> 53:15.431
They're already poisoning
the baby.

53:17.277 --> 53:19.768
No. I'm not listening to this.
Sarah.

53:20.155 --> 53:21.770
Stop it! Just stop it, okay?

53:22.700 --> 53:25.442
Do you hear yourself? You are
acting like a crazy person.

53:25.536 --> 53:28.528
Tearing up our floor.
Scaring me half to death.

53:28.622 --> 53:31.238
I know it's my job to support
you, but that does not mean

53:31.333 --> 53:33.745
you get to come into our
home, to our family

53:33.836 --> 53:36.748
and tell me that our unborn
child is being poisoned. No!

53:36.839 --> 53:39.296
I'm sorry. Can I please explain?

53:39.383 --> 53:41.123
Explain what? All of it.

53:41.927 --> 53:46.011
And if you still think I'm crazy,
I'll drop it. I swear to god.

53:48.684 --> 53:49.890
I swear to you.

54:06.410 --> 54:08.366
There is a man-made chemical

54:10.205 --> 54:12.617
that was invented
during the Manhattan project.

54:13.667 --> 54:16.158
It repelled the elements,
especially water.

54:16.795 --> 54:21.129
So they used it to make the first
ever waterproof coating for tanks.

54:21.216 --> 54:22.581
It was indestructible.

54:22.676 --> 54:26.760
Then some companies thought,
"hey, why just the battlefield?

54:26.847 --> 54:30.715
"Why not bring this chemical
into American homes?"

54:30.934 --> 54:32.390
Rob's here.
Tom: All right. Good.

54:33.312 --> 54:34.312
He'll see you now.

54:38.317 --> 54:40.103
Rob: Dupont was one
of those companies.

54:41.862 --> 54:44.399
So they took
this chemical, pfoa.

54:45.199 --> 54:46.860
They renamed it c-8.

54:47.868 --> 54:50.530
And they made their own
impenetrable coating,

54:50.621 --> 54:53.237
but not for tanks. For pans.

54:54.875 --> 54:56.615
They called it teflon.

54:57.211 --> 55:00.624
A shining symbol
of American ingenuity,

55:00.714 --> 55:02.921
made right here in the usa,

55:03.008 --> 55:05.090
in parkersburg, West Virginia.

55:07.012 --> 55:09.219
But right from the start,
something wasn't right.

55:09.932 --> 55:13.095
The men, and workers
who made teflon

55:13.185 --> 55:15.676
were coming down
with nausea, fevers.

55:15.771 --> 55:17.181
Dupont wanted to know why.

55:17.856 --> 55:20.518
So they laced cigarettes
with teflon.

55:20.609 --> 55:23.100
They told a group of their
workers, "hey, smoke these."

55:23.904 --> 55:25.735
Duponters did as they were told.

55:27.282 --> 55:29.318
Almost all of those men
were hospitalized.

55:33.914 --> 55:35.450
That's 1962.

55:35.999 --> 55:39.958
One year after teflon launched
and already dupont knew.

55:40.587 --> 55:44.250
The dust, they just sent right up the
smoke stacks, released into the air.

55:45.050 --> 55:47.632
The sludge, tossed
it into the Ohio.

55:47.719 --> 55:51.928
Or, uh, packed into drums and
chucked it into the chesapeake.

55:52.724 --> 55:54.885
But then their drums
started washing up.

55:55.394 --> 55:57.806
So, dupont starts
digging ditches

55:57.896 --> 55:59.852
on the grounds
of the Washington works plant.

55:59.940 --> 56:02.181
And in those pits, they dumped

56:02.276 --> 56:05.860
thousands of tons
of toxic c-8 sludge and dust.

56:06.321 --> 56:09.063
One of the men that they hired
to dig those ditches

56:09.157 --> 56:11.819
was wilbur tennant's
brother Jim.

56:12.703 --> 56:15.035
But they weren't the only ones
covering their tracks.

56:15.581 --> 56:19.324
3m who pioneered these
chemicals for scotchgard,

56:19.418 --> 56:20.783
they were testing them
on monkeys.

56:21.336 --> 56:22.746
Most of the monkeys died.

56:23.380 --> 56:25.746
It wasn't like dupont
didn't know that because

56:25.841 --> 56:28.173
they were doing
their own tests on rats.

56:29.052 --> 56:30.667
Watched their organs balloon.

56:31.930 --> 56:33.761
Now the rats
are getting cancers.

56:34.391 --> 56:37.975
Tested them on pregnant rats
and watched them give birth

56:38.061 --> 56:40.347
to pups with deformed eyes.

56:41.064 --> 56:44.272
So, they yanked all the young
women off the teflon line

56:44.776 --> 56:46.016
and never told them why.

56:50.365 --> 56:55.029
Sue Bailey's job was scrubbing
these huge steel vats

56:55.120 --> 56:58.157
where they held the liquid c-8.
She was pregnant.

56:58.624 --> 57:00.706
I love youl! Would you stop?

57:02.836 --> 57:07.205
Rob: She gave birth to a baby with
one nostril and a deformed eye.

57:07.299 --> 57:10.837
Remember how dupont had seen
those deformities in the rats?

57:14.056 --> 57:15.592
Oh, god. What about his eyes?

57:16.141 --> 57:18.223
Blue. Just like all newborns.

57:18.310 --> 57:20.676
But they're normal,
the lids, the pupils?

57:20.771 --> 57:24.229
Mr. bilott, relax. He's perfect.

57:25.025 --> 57:27.186
Hey. Hi, Charlie.

57:27.277 --> 57:29.859
Rob: So sue goes to dupont.

57:29.947 --> 57:32.689
She says, "why did you pull me
off the teflon line?

57:33.492 --> 57:38.111
"Did c-8 make my baby this
way?" "No," they tell her.

57:38.205 --> 57:42.539
Then all of her records from
her time at teflon disappear.

57:42.626 --> 57:47.336
One year later, they put all
of the women back on teflon

57:47.422 --> 57:50.164
and never say a thing.

57:56.807 --> 57:57.807
He's here.

58:02.062 --> 58:03.768
Rob: Dupont knew everything.

58:04.773 --> 58:08.231
They knew that the c-8
they put into the air

58:08.318 --> 58:10.309
and buried into the
ground for decades

58:10.404 --> 58:12.065
was causing cancers.

58:12.155 --> 58:15.898
They knew that their own workers
were getting these cancers.

58:15.993 --> 58:19.030
They knew that the consumers
too were being exposed

58:19.121 --> 58:22.454
and not just in teflon.
In paints,

58:22.916 --> 58:27.205
in fabrics, in,
uh, raincoats, boots.

58:28.839 --> 58:30.295
To this day...

58:32.342 --> 58:36.460
Rob: For 40 years you knew
c-8 was poison.

58:36.555 --> 58:39.968
You knew the "happy pan"
was a ticking time bomb.

58:40.559 --> 58:43.096
And you knew exactly why.

58:43.270 --> 58:45.511
Because c-8,
it stays in us forever.

58:48.942 --> 58:53.185
And knowing all of this,
still you did nothing because

58:53.780 --> 58:56.021
doing something,

58:56.908 --> 58:59.866
"would essentially
put the long-term viability

58:59.953 --> 59:03.946
"of this product's segment
on the line."

59:06.710 --> 59:08.996
You were making too much money.

59:09.921 --> 59:13.129
One billion dollars a year just
in profits, just in teflon.

59:14.426 --> 59:17.964
And so you pumped
millions more pounds

59:18.055 --> 59:21.218
of toxic c-8 into the air,
into the water

59:21.475 --> 59:24.467
so much so you could
actually see it foam.

59:25.312 --> 59:30.773
C-8 was everywhere. There was nowhere
left for you to contaminate.

59:34.905 --> 59:37.066
And that's when
they came to Jim.

59:37.741 --> 59:41.359
They knew he was sick and needed the
money and they needed his land.

59:42.079 --> 59:45.196
And when they got it,
they dug up all the c-8

59:45.373 --> 59:48.160
from every single pit
at Washington works.

59:48.251 --> 59:51.584
Fourteen million pounds
of toxic c-8 sludge

59:51.797 --> 59:55.005
and they dumped it, again.
This time right up there.

59:55.175 --> 59:58.167
Steps from your creek,
from your house.

59:59.012 --> 1:00:02.129
That's what your cows
have been drinking, Earl.

1:00:06.520 --> 1:00:08.727
Put 'em behind bars.

1:00:08.814 --> 1:00:10.520
Whole damn lot of 'em,
right in jail.

1:00:10.690 --> 1:00:12.021
I understand, believe me.

1:00:12.109 --> 1:00:15.101
But this is a civil case. The
most we can hope for is damages.

1:00:15.237 --> 1:00:19.230
Don't want no money!
Whole damn world need...

1:00:25.580 --> 1:00:28.572
Needs to see what they done.
You're right. They should.

1:00:30.168 --> 1:00:32.750
And it kills me that they won't.

1:00:33.797 --> 1:00:36.379
But that would mean
going to trial

1:00:36.550 --> 1:00:38.962
and proving
that c-8 killed your cows.

1:00:39.136 --> 1:00:41.673
And every scientist who knows
anything about any of this

1:00:41.847 --> 1:00:43.838
already works
for these chemical companies.

1:00:43.974 --> 1:00:46.386
That's not an accident, Earl.

1:00:46.977 --> 1:00:52.142
Earl, these companies, they have
all the money all the time,

1:00:52.232 --> 1:00:53.688
and they'll use it. Trust me.

1:00:53.817 --> 1:00:55.557
I know. I was one of them.

1:00:57.028 --> 1:00:59.440
You're still one of 'em.

1:01:02.576 --> 1:01:06.819
You can't be serious. You know
what I put on the line here?

1:01:06.997 --> 1:01:10.160
You want a prize? Some medal
'cause for once in your life

1:01:10.250 --> 1:01:12.662
you took the side
of the little guy?

1:01:13.086 --> 1:01:16.328
Sorry, no prize. All you get is
your share of this blood money.

1:01:16.631 --> 1:01:19.464
And you sleep real good tonight.
Talk to your family.

1:01:19.926 --> 1:01:22.167
It ain't just my cows
was poisoned.

1:01:22.262 --> 1:01:24.423
What do you think
I fed my family on?

1:01:24.639 --> 1:01:27.756
Wilbur, please.

1:01:29.352 --> 1:01:31.513
Leave this place!

1:01:32.856 --> 1:01:36.599
Start over. Give your family
a fighting chance!

1:01:36.776 --> 1:01:38.767
Too late for that.

1:01:41.698 --> 1:01:44.030
We got it, Sandra and me.
The cancer.

1:01:45.744 --> 1:01:47.735
Surprise, surprise.

1:02:43.760 --> 1:02:45.500
Sarah: In here.

1:02:51.559 --> 1:02:53.345
How'd it go?

1:02:55.522 --> 1:02:56.762
What's wrong?

1:02:57.607 --> 1:02:59.063
Rob?

1:02:59.901 --> 1:03:00.901
Rob, what is it?

1:03:06.866 --> 1:03:08.572
Sarah: What happened?
What happened?

1:03:09.202 --> 1:03:11.193
Oh, honey, honey, honey.

1:03:12.956 --> 1:03:15.368
Sarah: You saw a man hurting and

1:03:17.043 --> 1:03:19.455
you did the Christian thing.
You helped him.

1:03:19.963 --> 1:03:24.377
How? How?
Either he dies penniless

1:03:24.551 --> 1:03:27.509
or he lets dupont just keep
pillaging his community.

1:03:27.595 --> 1:03:29.005
How is that helping?

1:03:33.351 --> 1:03:35.342
Gotta get some sleep.

1:03:47.073 --> 1:03:50.031
I can't believe a freaking case
settlement could shut this up.

1:03:52.620 --> 1:03:55.362
Have you read their
confidentiality agreements?

1:03:56.249 --> 1:03:58.865
You've uncovered
a threat to the public.

1:03:59.461 --> 1:04:01.702
This goes beyond lawyering.

1:04:01.796 --> 1:04:04.082
That's... that's all
I know is lawyering.

1:04:04.174 --> 1:04:06.415
Fine. Then be the lawyer.

1:04:06.968 --> 1:04:08.458
You know dupont
better than anyone.

1:04:08.636 --> 1:04:09.876
What haven't they thought of?

1:05:09.823 --> 1:05:11.779
God. Jesus, Mary and Joseph.

1:05:12.283 --> 1:05:13.283
What is that?

1:05:13.368 --> 1:05:16.201
Rob: Uh, a memo
and 136 exhibits.

1:05:49.112 --> 1:05:51.023
Rob: Wil, Sandra,
this is your copy.

1:06:11.676 --> 1:06:15.339
The epa announced a public hearing
into this family of chemicals

1:06:15.430 --> 1:06:17.921
I've been looking into.
I heard about it from Tucker.

1:06:18.183 --> 1:06:20.390
Tom: Monsanto Tucker?
Union carbide now.

1:06:20.518 --> 1:06:21.558
He says to me, "is it true

1:06:21.603 --> 1:06:23.139
"that a taft lawyer sent a
phone book's

1:06:23.229 --> 1:06:24.665
"worth of confidential
dupont documents

1:06:24.689 --> 1:06:26.270
"to the entire
federal government?"

1:06:26.357 --> 1:06:28.939
Internal documents, not confidential.
Very different.

1:06:29.027 --> 1:06:31.109
So you're testifying.
Rob: I signed up to testify.

1:06:31.196 --> 1:06:32.196
And the next thing I hear

1:06:32.280 --> 1:06:34.271
is dupont has petitioned a judge

1:06:34.365 --> 1:06:37.027
to stop me from testifying,
from flying to d.C,

1:06:37.118 --> 1:06:38.179
from even picking up the phone

1:06:38.203 --> 1:06:39.283
they filed for a gag order.

1:06:39.370 --> 1:06:41.110
Yes! This is what
we're up against.

1:06:41.206 --> 1:06:42.446
Jesus. Tom: David.

1:06:42.540 --> 1:06:43.601
Come on, Tom.
What do you expect?

1:06:43.625 --> 1:06:44.705
Where do we stand?

1:06:44.792 --> 1:06:46.623
Well, the judge rejected
the gag order,

1:06:46.711 --> 1:06:48.201
so I fly out Monday.

1:06:48.671 --> 1:06:52.163
Nice. I guess we'll
just watch on c-span.

1:06:54.469 --> 1:06:55.959
You ever do
anything like this again,

1:06:56.054 --> 1:06:59.717
I will cut your balls off and
serve them to dupont myself.

1:07:00.099 --> 1:07:01.509
Get out of here.

1:07:04.521 --> 1:07:05.886
Good luck in Washington.

1:07:07.148 --> 1:07:08.433
Thanks, Tom.

1:07:08.942 --> 1:07:12.730
Rob: This material
is a perfluoro...

1:07:12.904 --> 1:07:14.735
Or a pfoa.

1:07:14.906 --> 1:07:18.364
It's also known as fc 143,

1:07:19.327 --> 1:07:22.569
ammonium perfluorooctanoates.

1:07:22.664 --> 1:07:27.408
It has been shown
by dupont's own science

1:07:28.461 --> 1:07:30.577
that pfoa c-8

1:07:31.589 --> 1:07:35.673
is possibly life threatening
to human health.

1:07:36.094 --> 1:07:41.634
We are asking this agency
to do something.

1:08:02.370 --> 1:08:04.611
The presidential election
in four decades.

1:08:04.789 --> 1:08:06.529
Just look at these latest polls.

1:08:07.041 --> 1:08:08.681
Joe: Did you forget
to pay the water bill?

1:08:09.586 --> 1:08:10.746
Darlene: What?

1:08:10.837 --> 1:08:12.919
You forget to pay
the water bill?

1:08:14.549 --> 1:08:15.880
No.

1:08:16.718 --> 1:08:18.083
We got a notice.

1:08:18.636 --> 1:08:19.842
What's it say?

1:08:21.931 --> 1:08:24.843
"Pfoa is a persistent chemical

1:08:24.934 --> 1:08:26.470
"that is slow to be eliminated

1:08:26.561 --> 1:08:29.928
"from the blood stream of people
who have been exposed to it.

1:08:30.440 --> 1:08:32.180
"The dupont company has advised

1:08:32.275 --> 1:08:35.517
"the lubeck water district
that low concentrations

1:08:35.612 --> 1:08:38.570
"have been found
in the district's Wells.

1:08:38.656 --> 1:08:39.936
"Dupont has advised the district

1:08:39.991 --> 1:08:43.028
"that it is confident
these levels are safe."

1:08:44.203 --> 1:08:46.034
What the hell does that mean?

1:08:47.874 --> 1:08:49.785
Joe: A letter came last fall.

1:08:50.376 --> 1:08:52.662
James: Made no sense to me,
so I started making calls.

1:08:52.754 --> 1:08:55.040
Darlene: I told Joe don't
kick that hornet's nest.

1:08:55.673 --> 1:08:58.289
It's not like we didn't know
what we'd signed up for.

1:08:59.594 --> 1:09:00.709
Sarah: What do you mean?

1:09:01.471 --> 1:09:03.462
Oh, I was married before Joe

1:09:04.182 --> 1:09:06.093
to a chemist at dupont.

1:09:06.643 --> 1:09:08.429
Dream job. Paid real well.

1:09:08.519 --> 1:09:11.511
And the perks!
Presents for no reason.

1:09:11.606 --> 1:09:15.064
We'd get this catalogue.
Just pick whatever you want.

1:09:16.027 --> 1:09:17.312
And little stuff.

1:09:17.403 --> 1:09:18.813
Like he'd bring home this soap,

1:09:18.905 --> 1:09:20.486
this miracle powder.

1:09:20.573 --> 1:09:22.613
You put it in the washing
machine or the dishwasher,

1:09:22.700 --> 1:09:24.660
just wipes stuff clean
like you would not believe.

1:09:25.662 --> 1:09:28.119
One day he comes home and says,

1:09:28.206 --> 1:09:29.946
"can't bring that stuff
home no more."

1:09:30.041 --> 1:09:31.781
"Why?" won't tell me.

1:09:32.126 --> 1:09:34.333
Then he'd get sick for weeks.

1:09:35.129 --> 1:09:37.211
The teflon flu,
the guys would call it.

1:09:37.965 --> 1:09:40.081
We knew something wasn't right.

1:09:40.593 --> 1:09:43.426
But this house,
we bought it just by

1:09:43.513 --> 1:09:46.596
showing the bank
my husband's dupont ID.

1:09:46.683 --> 1:09:49.971
Put both our kids
through college. Engineers.

1:09:51.604 --> 1:09:54.311
In this town, that doesn't
come without a price.

1:09:54.649 --> 1:09:57.356
My brother Kenny
didn't know that price.

1:09:57.527 --> 1:09:59.563
He joined dupont at 19.

1:09:59.654 --> 1:10:01.986
Died on the operating table
two years later.

1:10:02.448 --> 1:10:05.531
Ulcerative colitis. Darlene:
Just like Dan Schiller had.

1:10:05.618 --> 1:10:06.903
Who's Dan?

1:10:07.078 --> 1:10:09.694
Darlene: A chemist at dupont.
Worked with my ex-husband.

1:10:10.164 --> 1:10:12.906
Joe: And Roger, what's his name?

1:10:13.000 --> 1:10:14.490
Darlene: Wilkins, the foreman.

1:10:14.627 --> 1:10:16.868
Steven gellar. Randy field.

1:10:16.963 --> 1:10:19.579
Randy's was kidney cancer.
He survived.

1:10:19.674 --> 1:10:22.211
His wife didn't.
No, June's was thyroid.

1:10:22.301 --> 1:10:23.882
It was supposed to be treatable.

1:10:24.262 --> 1:10:25.593
They didn't catch it in time.

1:10:25.680 --> 1:10:27.921
But they caught it in their son.

1:10:29.976 --> 1:10:32.058
Rob: Were your children
born healthy?

1:10:32.145 --> 1:10:34.181
Yes. Yes, they were. Good.

1:10:34.355 --> 1:10:38.268
But we wanted
a third and couldn't.

1:10:38.359 --> 1:10:39.565
I went to my doctor.

1:10:39.652 --> 1:10:42.359
He says, "you need a hysterectomy.
You need it right away."

1:10:44.240 --> 1:10:45.400
I'm so sorry.

1:10:45.491 --> 1:10:47.072
Bad luck, I guess.

1:10:48.786 --> 1:10:50.151
I was 36.

1:10:51.581 --> 1:10:52.787
Rob: Mr. kiger,

1:10:52.874 --> 1:10:55.081
you think I could get
a copy of that letter?

1:11:07.597 --> 1:11:09.553
What's wrong with your hand?

1:11:09.932 --> 1:11:12.093
Nothing. It's fine.

1:11:17.106 --> 1:11:18.971
Whoa, Rob?

1:11:21.110 --> 1:11:22.816
Rob, what are you doing?

1:11:24.781 --> 1:11:27.022
I mean, it's not enough
to poison these people?

