1:13:08.009 --> 1:13:10.295
This is what dupont
considers safe.

1:13:10.678 --> 1:13:13.169
That's something like
one drop of water

1:13:13.264 --> 1:13:15.346
in an olympic size
swimming pool.

1:13:15.433 --> 1:13:17.924
In other words,
even a trace of c-8

1:13:18.019 --> 1:13:19.930
renders water unsafe.

1:13:20.021 --> 1:13:22.353
But dupont told
the local water authority,

1:13:23.566 --> 1:13:25.557
"your Wells have got even
less than that."

1:13:25.651 --> 1:13:27.733
Except that was a lie. A lie?

1:13:27.820 --> 1:13:30.436
Yes. Dupont has been
secretly testing

1:13:30.531 --> 1:13:31.862
these Wells for decades.

1:13:31.949 --> 1:13:34.907
They knew they had
contaminated those Wells

1:13:34.994 --> 1:13:37.906
up to six times that level.

1:13:37.997 --> 1:13:40.659
And thanks to the tennant
case, now we know too.

1:13:40.750 --> 1:13:43.366
David: Hold on. This stuff
is unregulated, right?

1:13:43.461 --> 1:13:44.997
I mean, as far as
epa's concerned,

1:13:45.087 --> 1:13:47.123
it might as well be Rose petals.

1:13:47.214 --> 1:13:49.455
The epa hasn't
set a standard, that's true,

1:13:49.550 --> 1:13:51.211
but dupont did.

1:13:51.427 --> 1:13:54.260
And all the law requires
to win a case like this,

1:13:54.347 --> 1:13:56.588
is to show that dupont exceeded

1:13:56.682 --> 1:13:59.219
what dupont itself
considers safe.

1:13:59.435 --> 1:14:00.595
Self-regulation.

1:14:00.728 --> 1:14:02.664
Managing partner: If what you're
saying is right... it is right.

1:14:02.688 --> 1:14:06.055
Then why would dupont tell this
water district anything at all?

1:14:06.150 --> 1:14:07.606
Seems to me that they're being

1:14:07.693 --> 1:14:09.433
a good corporate citizen here.

1:14:09.862 --> 1:14:12.854
That's how long
you have to file suit.

1:14:13.282 --> 1:14:14.567
One year from the moment

1:14:14.659 --> 1:14:17.196
you realize your water's
been contaminated.

1:14:17.662 --> 1:14:21.746
This letter looks like it's telling
people their water is safe.

1:14:21.832 --> 1:14:24.995
In fact, it's notifying them
that it isn't.

1:14:25.086 --> 1:14:26.747
Dupont has started the clock.

1:14:27.129 --> 1:14:28.244
David: Smart.

1:14:28.839 --> 1:14:29.954
We would've counseled that.

1:14:30.049 --> 1:14:32.085
Rob: It was sent 11 months ago.

1:14:32.176 --> 1:14:34.633
The moment they realized
we knew.

1:14:35.304 --> 1:14:37.511
In 30 days, they're home free.

1:14:37.598 --> 1:14:40.180
So that's the proposed
case in brief.

1:14:40.267 --> 1:14:42.007
But there's something else
to consider.

1:14:42.103 --> 1:14:43.343
Partner: You think?

1:14:43.646 --> 1:14:44.726
Rob.

1:14:44.814 --> 1:14:47.726
C-8 bio-accumulates.
It builds up inside of us.

1:14:48.109 --> 1:14:50.395
Some class members
who aren't sick today

1:14:51.654 --> 1:14:53.110
will get sick tomorrow.

1:14:53.197 --> 1:14:55.939
We need a way to protect
them into the future.

1:14:56.033 --> 1:14:58.136
Jesus, Tom! If you're even thinking
about using medical monitoring...

1:14:58.160 --> 1:15:00.492
Hold on. Hold on.

1:15:00.579 --> 1:15:04.197
Medical monitoring
is a claim now permitted

1:15:04.291 --> 1:15:05.497
in West Virginia courts.

1:15:05.584 --> 1:15:07.540
Partner: Oh, come on.
Let's hear him out.

1:15:07.628 --> 1:15:10.290
It say if a company
exposes a community

1:15:10.381 --> 1:15:11.996
to something
that makes them sick,

1:15:12.091 --> 1:15:15.299
they must monitor the health of
that community indefinitely.

1:15:15.386 --> 1:15:19.254
Everybody get that? You're creating
liability from mere exposure.

1:15:19.348 --> 1:15:21.054
It's also unprecedented.

1:15:21.142 --> 1:15:23.258
Exactly! Which is why
not six months ago,

1:15:23.352 --> 1:15:25.013
we fought tooth and nail
against it.

1:15:25.104 --> 1:15:27.811
And you lost.
Our clients have the right

1:15:27.898 --> 1:15:29.729
to avail themselves of the law.

1:15:29.817 --> 1:15:32.308
Potential clients.

1:15:36.490 --> 1:15:37.490
James: Okay.

1:15:38.117 --> 1:15:41.405
I know you, Rob.
I know your passion.

1:15:42.163 --> 1:15:44.404
You got a great settlement
for your farmer.

1:15:44.498 --> 1:15:45.829
You should be proud of that.

1:15:46.792 --> 1:15:50.376
And perhaps as the newest
partner at this table,

1:15:50.463 --> 1:15:51.999
I should be more circumspect.

1:15:52.089 --> 1:15:56.173
But what he's proposing here is

1:15:56.802 --> 1:15:59.043
nothing less than a shakedown

1:15:59.138 --> 1:16:02.130
of an iconic American company.
We do not represent dupont.

1:16:02.224 --> 1:16:04.306
No, you don't represent anyone.

1:16:05.978 --> 1:16:07.809
Is this what we have become?

1:16:07.897 --> 1:16:10.639
Plaintiff's attorneys.
Ambulance chasers.

1:16:10.733 --> 1:16:12.653
Why don't you just admit it?
Rob, you wanna flip.

1:16:12.735 --> 1:16:14.851
You wanna take everything
that you know

1:16:14.945 --> 1:16:17.357
about how
chemical companies operate

1:16:17.448 --> 1:16:19.905
and turn it against dupont.
Like an informant.

1:16:19.992 --> 1:16:21.178
That's enough.
James: Isn't that right?

1:16:21.202 --> 1:16:22.533
Tom: Okay! Isn't that right?

1:16:22.620 --> 1:16:23.985
Isn't that right? Yes.

1:16:24.538 --> 1:16:27.951
Okay, then, I...
I say we take a vote

1:16:28.042 --> 1:16:30.158
and determine whether or not

1:16:30.252 --> 1:16:31.742
we continue in the tradition

1:16:31.837 --> 1:16:34.169
that has distinguished this
firm from everyone else...

1:16:34.256 --> 1:16:36.713
Tom: Okay, I'm running
this meeting. Okay?

1:16:37.384 --> 1:16:38.384
You got that?

1:16:39.386 --> 1:16:41.047
Has anyone even read
the evidence

1:16:41.138 --> 1:16:42.218
this man has collected?

1:16:43.432 --> 1:16:45.718
The willful negligence,
the corruption?

1:16:47.186 --> 1:16:48.186
Read it!

1:16:48.979 --> 1:16:50.979
And then tell me we should
be sitting on our asses!

1:16:51.649 --> 1:16:55.517
That's the reason
why Americans hate lawyers.

1:16:56.320 --> 1:16:59.357
This is the crap that fuels
the Ralph naders of the world.

1:16:59.448 --> 1:17:02.155
We should want to nail dupont.

1:17:03.035 --> 1:17:04.991
All of us should!

1:17:05.079 --> 1:17:07.286
American business is better
than this, gentlemen.

1:17:07.373 --> 1:17:09.989
And when it's not,
we should hold them to it.

1:17:10.084 --> 1:17:12.166
That's how you build
faith in the system.

1:17:13.546 --> 1:17:16.288
We're always arguing
that companies are people.

1:17:17.341 --> 1:17:20.799
Well, these people
have crossed the line!

1:17:21.929 --> 1:17:23.590
To hell with them!

1:17:27.309 --> 1:17:28.799
Harry: It may come as a surprise

1:17:28.894 --> 1:17:31.806
to corporate defense types
like yourselves,

1:17:31.897 --> 1:17:33.762
but there's more to the law
than just flooding

1:17:33.858 --> 1:17:35.439
the other side in papers.

1:17:35.526 --> 1:17:38.734
From where I sit,
you have to touch people.

1:17:39.488 --> 1:17:41.399
These girls,
they handle the calls

1:17:41.490 --> 1:17:43.651
from the class action members.

1:17:43.742 --> 1:17:46.199
And there's thousands of 'em
on any given case.

1:17:46.829 --> 1:17:49.912
And it's here that we come
to know their pain.

1:17:49.999 --> 1:17:51.535
Isn't that right, Hazel?

1:17:51.625 --> 1:17:54.913
Yes. We hear it every day

1:17:55.004 --> 1:17:58.167
and it's my job to make
a jury feel that pain.

1:17:58.257 --> 1:18:00.748
Not out of pity,
but out of fear.

1:18:01.302 --> 1:18:03.634
Whatever it is
that happened to my client,

1:18:03.721 --> 1:18:05.507
that juror has to think,

1:18:06.557 --> 1:18:08.093
"that could happen to me."

1:18:08.267 --> 1:18:09.677
Rob: You just keep hammering it.

1:18:09.768 --> 1:18:11.929
One part per billion.
One part per billion.

1:18:12.021 --> 1:18:14.433
It's their own documents.
Their own scientists.

1:18:14.523 --> 1:18:15.558
Harry: Absolutely.

1:18:15.649 --> 1:18:18.061
Rob: They set that standard,
they have to live with it.

1:18:18.152 --> 1:18:20.143
Harry: Yeah, I think
we can relax, Rob,

1:18:20.237 --> 1:18:23.479
though, there's no way they're gonna
prevail with a motion to dismiss.

1:18:23.574 --> 1:18:25.155
This is procedural.

1:18:25.492 --> 1:18:27.403
It's nonsense.
We'll get a trial today.

1:18:30.122 --> 1:18:32.363
Rob: Okay, I'll catch
you guys in there.

1:18:35.961 --> 1:18:37.292
Wilbur: I wouldn't drink that.

1:18:40.883 --> 1:18:41.883
Earl.

1:18:44.011 --> 1:18:45.217
How ya doing?

1:18:46.222 --> 1:18:47.428
Still here.

1:18:49.266 --> 1:18:50.676
That's somethin', right?

1:18:51.810 --> 1:18:53.596
Yes, that's something.

1:18:54.563 --> 1:18:55.803
Sandra: Good to see ya, Robbie.

1:18:59.485 --> 1:19:00.725
Can't let 'em

1:19:02.238 --> 1:19:03.444
shut you down.

1:19:05.449 --> 1:19:07.906
I won't. I promise.

1:19:08.702 --> 1:19:10.033
Whole world

1:19:11.705 --> 1:19:13.411
needs to know.

1:19:15.542 --> 1:19:18.249
They will, Earl. They will.

1:19:20.339 --> 1:19:23.206
Hey, Rob? It's time.

1:19:25.594 --> 1:19:27.334
I have to go.

1:19:43.779 --> 1:19:45.394
We are here
on defendant's motion

1:19:45.489 --> 1:19:49.107
to dismiss the case
brought by Mr. kiger, et al.

1:19:50.369 --> 1:19:54.078
Now, which one of you
is Mr. Wallace?

1:19:54.832 --> 1:19:56.447
Edward Wallace, your honor,

1:19:56.542 --> 1:19:59.079
on behalf of the e.I.
Dupont de nemours and company,

1:19:59.169 --> 1:20:00.625
better known as dupont.

1:20:00.754 --> 1:20:02.244
Yes, I've heard of it.

1:20:02.339 --> 1:20:04.000
Your motion. Thank you.

1:20:05.009 --> 1:20:08.877
Your honor, we're here today because
of a uniquely American invention.

1:20:09.638 --> 1:20:10.638
Teflon.

1:20:11.098 --> 1:20:13.805
Since 1961, teflon
has liberated housewives...

1:20:13.892 --> 1:20:16.929
No, no, no.
Excuse me. Homemakers...

1:20:17.021 --> 1:20:19.307
This is a courtroom,
Mr. Wallace.

1:20:19.398 --> 1:20:21.138
Not the home shopping network.

1:20:23.319 --> 1:20:25.275
Plaintiffs have alleged
that dupont

1:20:25.362 --> 1:20:27.398
did not meet
its own standard of safety

1:20:27.489 --> 1:20:29.946
with regard to the level of c-8

1:20:30.034 --> 1:20:31.319
in the local water supply.

1:20:32.161 --> 1:20:33.571
That's irrelevant, your honor.

1:20:34.246 --> 1:20:35.656
We ask you to dismiss on grounds

1:20:35.748 --> 1:20:37.659
that the only standard
that matters,

1:20:37.750 --> 1:20:40.412
is the one that elected
government deems safe.

1:20:40.502 --> 1:20:41.662
Rob: Not if it's unregulated.

1:20:41.712 --> 1:20:43.794
It's government's job
to make these determinations.

1:20:43.881 --> 1:20:45.417
Not any one company.
It's a trap.

1:20:45.507 --> 1:20:46.872
They can't revert back to...

1:20:46.967 --> 1:20:48.082
I got it.

1:20:48.177 --> 1:20:49.963
Is there a problem,
Mr. deitzler?

1:20:50.054 --> 1:20:51.760
Apologies, your honor,

1:20:51.847 --> 1:20:55.510
but dupont has been hiding
the dangers of this chemical

1:20:55.601 --> 1:20:57.933
from the government
for a while now.

1:20:58.020 --> 1:21:00.477
And they're asking you
to let them off the hook

1:21:00.564 --> 1:21:02.850
because they've succeeded
in their strategy.

1:21:02.941 --> 1:21:05.023
Government doesn't regulate c-8.

1:21:05.110 --> 1:21:06.470
Wallace: Actually,
that's not true.

1:21:06.570 --> 1:21:07.570
No, no.

1:21:07.654 --> 1:21:09.690
The West Virginia's
c-8 working group

1:21:09.782 --> 1:21:11.272
has just issued a standard.

1:21:11.950 --> 1:21:13.110
Here with us today,

1:21:13.202 --> 1:21:15.122
is the governmental official
who led that effort,

1:21:15.496 --> 1:21:17.032
Dr. Mary sue kimball.

1:21:19.625 --> 1:21:22.116
And, Dr. kimball,
as a senior member

1:21:22.211 --> 1:21:24.452
of the state's department
of environmental protection,

1:21:24.546 --> 1:21:26.082
isn't it, in fact, your duty,

1:21:26.215 --> 1:21:28.415
to protect the citizens of West Virginia...
Mr. Wallace.

1:21:29.426 --> 1:21:30.541
I'll cut to the chase.

1:21:32.221 --> 1:21:33.961
What is the level of c-8
in drinking water

1:21:34.056 --> 1:21:36.217
that the state of West Virginia

1:21:38.602 --> 1:21:39.996
Harry: Watch it go from one
part per billion to?

1:21:40.020 --> 1:21:41.020
Five. Ten?

1:21:41.105 --> 1:21:42.766
150 parts per billion.

1:21:46.985 --> 1:21:49.977
Of all six water districts
represented in this suit,

1:21:50.364 --> 1:21:52.355
do they fall below
this maximum level?

1:21:52.449 --> 1:21:53.449
Well below.

1:21:54.660 --> 1:21:55.695
Nothing else, your honor.

1:21:57.079 --> 1:21:58.740
Your witness, Mr. deitzler.

1:21:58.831 --> 1:22:00.287
Wait. Who's on
the working group?

1:22:00.374 --> 1:22:01.705
Dupont, of course, and who else?

1:22:01.792 --> 1:22:03.186
Who did the water testing?
Mr. deitzler?

1:22:03.210 --> 1:22:04.871
When was it done?
One moment, judge.

1:22:04.962 --> 1:22:06.293
Rob: What was the sample size?

1:22:06.380 --> 1:22:07.460
We should be able to see...

1:22:07.506 --> 1:22:11.419
Going once, going twice...

1:22:11.510 --> 1:22:15.423
Dr. kimball, who were
the members of this cabal

1:22:15.514 --> 1:22:17.129
you call the c-8 working group?

1:22:17.224 --> 1:22:18.680
Objection.

1:22:19.017 --> 1:22:20.553
Cool it, Mr. deitzler.

1:22:22.104 --> 1:22:23.435
Go ahead, Dr. kimball.

1:22:23.897 --> 1:22:25.307
Agency officials,

1:22:25.399 --> 1:22:29.062
representatives of the scientific
community, um, stakeholders.

1:22:29.153 --> 1:22:30.893
Stakeholders?
Which stakeholders?

1:22:30.988 --> 1:22:34.446
Oh, wait, let me guess.
It rhymes with bouffant?

1:22:35.617 --> 1:22:37.357
Dupont is a stakeholder. Yes.

1:22:37.453 --> 1:22:38.613
So, I see.

1:22:38.704 --> 1:22:40.945
So, don't you find it peculiar
that on the Eve

1:22:41.457 --> 1:22:43.118
of a class action lawsuit,

1:22:43.208 --> 1:22:46.700
where dupont might be
considered liable

1:22:46.795 --> 1:22:49.286
for poisoning this community,

1:22:49.381 --> 1:22:52.214
they get you
to come in here suddenly

1:22:52.301 --> 1:22:56.089
and reverse decades of their
so-called heralded science?

1:22:57.222 --> 1:22:59.178
That's false.
I don't work for dupont.

1:22:59.266 --> 1:23:00.506
I didn't say you did.

1:23:01.351 --> 1:23:03.467
But now you bring it up,
we'll check back in a month.

1:23:03.562 --> 1:23:05.322
Your honor... you honestly,
was gonna plan on

1:23:05.355 --> 1:23:10.190
telling this community that they
can drink 150 times more c-8?

1:23:10.277 --> 1:23:11.983
I mean, come on,
people, bottoms up.

1:23:12.070 --> 1:23:13.070
Honestly, judge...

1:23:13.155 --> 1:23:15.316
All right, Mr. deitzler, enough.

1:23:16.575 --> 1:23:18.065
We'll be unveiling
the new standard

1:23:18.160 --> 1:23:19.616
at an upcoming public hearing.

1:23:20.287 --> 1:23:23.199
Unveiling. Oh,
that sounds like a party.

1:23:24.041 --> 1:23:25.041
We'll be there!

1:23:31.048 --> 1:23:33.790
Their safety standards thing,
that's all a sham.

1:23:33.884 --> 1:23:35.624
Thanks to the judge's decision,

1:23:35.719 --> 1:23:37.630
we will have our day in court.

1:23:37.721 --> 1:23:38.927
Man in crowd: Yes, we will!

1:23:39.014 --> 1:23:41.346
Because if the state
of West Virginia

1:23:41.433 --> 1:23:43.298
won't stop
the dupont corporation

1:23:43.393 --> 1:23:45.634
from literally
poisoning its citizens,

1:23:45.729 --> 1:23:49.062
then we, the citizens,
will stop them ourselves.

